</nav><section class="hero" id="hero">
  <p class="hero-eyebrow">Research Report &middot; JSPS KAKENHI JP 20KK0300 / JP 20K13914</p>
  <h1>Adverse Childhood Experiences &amp; Resilience Development in Ethnic Minority Preschool Children</h1>
  <p class="hero-sub">The role of parental care, early childhood education, and community support in Chiang Mai and Chiang Rai, Northern Thailand.</p>
  <p class="hero-authors">Prapassara Thanosawan, PhD (University of Sydney)<br>
  Nuttapa Thanosawan, PhD (Waseda University)<br>
  March 2024</p>
  <div class="hero-stats">
    <div><div class="hero-stat-num">224</div><div class="hero-stat-label">total participants in the study</div></div>
    <div><div class="hero-stat-num">149</div><div class="hero-stat-label">questionnaire respondents &mdash; parents &amp; teachers</div></div>
    <div><div class="hero-stat-num">65</div><div class="hero-stat-label">semi-structured interviews</div></div>
    <div><div class="hero-stat-num">79</div><div class="hero-stat-label">questionnaire items modelled with GLMs</div></div>
  </div>
  <div class="scroll-cue"><span class="line"></span><span>scroll</span></div>
</section>
<section class="block band-a" id="abstract">
<div class="block-inner">
<h2 class="sec-title">Abstract</h2>

<p>Ethnic minority children in Northern Thailand are exposed to elevated rates of Adverse Childhood Experiences (ACEs), yet little research has examined the protective factors that support resilience in this population. This mixed-methods study investigated how parental care, early childhood education, and community support relate to perceptions of resilience among ethnic minority children in Chiang Mai and Chiang Rai provinces. Quantitative data were collected from 50 parents/caregivers and 99 teachers/practitioners using structured questionnaires, and qualitative data were collected through semi-structured interviews. Generalised linear models (GLMs) tested associations between demographic and contextual predictors and survey responses; thematic analysis was used to identify resilience-promoting strategies described by parents and teachers. Demographic and contextual predictors significantly improved model fit for 31 of 48 parent-questionnaire items (65%) and 11 of 31 teacher-questionnaire items (35%). Thematic analysis identified active listening, promotion of autonomy, and consistent emotional and physical presence as central parental strategies, and safe classroom environments, emotional-regulation instruction, and strengths-based teaching as central teacher strategies. Findings suggest that parental and educational predictors of resilience-related perceptions differ in strength and pattern between caregivers and educators, with implications for the design of family-centred and school-based interventions for ethnic minority children affected by ACEs.</p>
<p><em>Keywords:</em> adverse childhood experiences, resilience, ethnic minority children, early childhood education, Thailand</p>

<div class="ack-note"><p class="ack-label">Acknowledgements</p><p>This research was supported by Grants-in-Aid from the Japan Society for the Promotion of Science (JSPS KAKENHI JP 20KK0300 and JP 20K13914). We thank the parents, caregivers, teachers, and practitioners in Chiang Mai and Chiang Rai who generously shared their time and experiences, without whom this study would not have been possible.</p></div>
</div>
</section>

<section class="block band-b" id="introduction">
<div class="block-inner">
<h2 class="sec-title">Introduction</h2>

<p>Adverse Childhood Experiences (ACEs) — including abuse, neglect, and household dysfunction — are associated with substantial short- and long-term harm to health, wellbeing, and developmental trajectories (Danese &amp; McEwen, 2012; Felitti et al., 1998). Resilience, broadly defined as the capacity to adapt and thrive despite adversity, has been identified as a key factor that can buffer children against the negative sequelae of ACEs (Ortiz, 2019). Children from ethnic minority communities are frequently exposed to compounding sources of adversity — socioeconomic hardship, discrimination, and limited access to services — that increase both their exposure to ACEs and the urgency of identifying protective factors specific to their circumstances (Phakakorn et al., 2018, 2019).</p>
<p>Despite a substantial international literature on ACEs, comparatively little research has examined how parental care, early childhood education, and community support interact to shape resilience among ethnic minority children in Southeast Asia. This study addresses that gap by examining ethnic minority communities in Chiang Mai and Chiang Rai provinces in Northern Thailand, drawing on the perspectives of parents/caregivers and teachers/practitioners who support these children directly.</p>
<h3 class="sub" id="research-questions">Research Questions</h3>
<p>This study was guided by four sets of research questions:</p>
<ol type="1">
<li><strong>Challenges and manifestations of ACEs.</strong> What specific challenges do children, parents, and educators in ethnic minority communities face in relation to ACEs, and how do cultural, social, and economic factors shape these challenges?</li>
<li><strong>Parental care and resilience.</strong> How does parental care influence resilience and healthy development among ethnic minority children, and what contextual factors shape parenting practices?</li>
<li><strong>Early childhood education.</strong> How does access to early childhood education contribute to resilience, and which programme features matter most for children exposed to ACEs?</li>
<li><strong>Community support systems.</strong> What community support systems are currently available to these families, and how might they be strengthened?</li>
</ol>
<h3 class="sub" id="research-purposes">Research Purposes</h3>
<p>The study aimed to identify protective factors associated with resilience in ethnic minority children exposed to ACEs, and to translate these findings into guidance for early intervention. Two data sources were used to this end. Semi-structured interviews with parents and teachers were analysed thematically, using an inductive approach to identify themes describing how resilience is fostered in practice (Creswell &amp; Creswell, 2018). Questionnaire surveys collected demographic information, perceptions of ACEs, parental care practices, engagement with early childhood education and welfare services, and perceived barriers to support; responses were analysed using generalised linear models to test which contextual and demographic factors were associated with item-level responses.</p>
<p>Early childhood education is a particular focus of this study because, in the Thai context, enrolment in registered preschools can determine children’s later access to public schooling and identification documentation — with material consequences for socioeconomic integration that extend well beyond early learning outcomes (Phakakorn et al., 2018; Walker &amp; Walsh, 2015). Schools and early childhood settings are also where many at-risk children first come into contact with adults positioned to recognise and respond to signs of adversity (Walker &amp; Walsh, 2015), making the school-family relationship a central object of inquiry in this study.</p>

</div>
</section>
<section class="block band-a" id="significance-of-the-study">
<div class="block-inner">
<h2 class="sec-title">Significance of the Study</h2>

<p>This research contributes to four audiences. For <strong>families and communities</strong>, the findings identify culturally grounded, practical strategies that parents already use to support resilience, which can inform peer- and community-based dissemination. For <strong>educators and practitioners</strong>, the findings clarify which trauma-informed practices and classroom strategies are most consistently described as effective by teachers working with ethnic minority children. For <strong>policymakers</strong>, the study provides empirical grounding for resourcing decisions around early childhood education and welfare services in marginalised regions of Northern Thailand. For <strong>the ACEs literature</strong>, the study extends existing research — conducted predominantly in North American and European contexts — to an understudied population, and reports parent- and teacher-level data side by side, allowing direct comparison between caregiving and educational perspectives on the same construct.</p>

</div>
</section>

<section class="block band-b" id="literature-review">
<div class="block-inner">
<h2 class="sec-title">Literature Review</h2>

<h3 class="sub" id="aces-and-long-term-outcomes">ACEs and Long-Term Outcomes</h3>
<p>The foundational ACE Study surveyed more than 17,000 adults about seven categories of childhood adversity and found a strong, graded relationship between cumulative ACE exposure and later-life risk for leading causes of death and disease, independent of other demographic factors (Felitti et al., 1998). Subsequent work extended this dose–response model to mental health, cognitive function, and socioeconomic outcomes, and showed that the consequences of ACEs are not distributed evenly: historically disadvantaged groups tend to carry a disproportionate share of both ACE exposure and its downstream effects (Danese &amp; McEwen, 2012). Individuals with six or more ACEs face substantially elevated odds of alcoholism, substance use, depression, and suicide attempt, and those with the highest ACE scores show up to a twelvefold increase in risk for conditions such as heart disease, cancer, and chronic lung disease relative to those with no reported ACEs (Felitti &amp; Anda, 2010).</p>
<p>Biologically, ACEs are understood to disrupt <em>allostasis</em> — the body’s adaptive stress-regulation system — producing dysregulation in hormonal and immune function, altered brain development, and accelerated cellular ageing, which together compound risk for disease across the lifespan (Danese &amp; McEwen, 2012). Behaviourally and psychosocially, ACEs are associated with increased risk of psychosocial disorder in adulthood (Maughan &amp; McCarthy, 1997), early-onset behavioural problems — observed in approximately 70% of children with three or more ACEs by age six (Clarkson Freeman, 2014) — and reduced adaptive behaviour and academic achievement in middle childhood (McKelvey et al., 2018). Associations between ACE exposure and adult aggression and lowered self-esteem have also been documented, with physical abuse and bullying showing the strongest negative association with self-esteem (Khodabandeh et al., 2018).</p>
<p>Taken together, this literature establishes ACEs as a robust, multi-system determinant of health and developmental risk, and underscores the importance of early detection and intervention in disrupting the transmission of harm across the lifespan and across generations (Felitti &amp; Anda, 2010).</p>
<h3 class="sub" id="structural-disparities-facing-ethnic-minority-communities-in-thailand">Structural Disparities Facing Ethnic Minority Communities in Thailand</h3>
<p>Ethnic minority communities in Northern Thailand face compounding structural disadvantages that elevate both ACE exposure and barriers to support. In <strong>education</strong>, financial constraints, geographic isolation, and cultural barriers contribute to lower enrolment and higher dropout rates than the national average; in some cases, children are denied primary school enrolment because they did not attend kindergarten, revealing a structural gap in the educational pipeline (Phakakorn et al., 2018). In <strong>healthcare</strong>, geographic remoteness and limited financial resources are associated with disproportionate rates of malnutrition, preventable disease, and maternal mortality relative to national averages (Ratanasuwan et al., 2020). In <strong>housing</strong>, overcrowded and poorly maintained dwellings increase exposure to environmental hazards, compounding existing socioeconomic disadvantage (Phakakorn et al., 2019).</p>
<p>Government programmes addressing these disparities exist but are frequently constrained by limited resourcing, inconsistent implementation, and insufficient cultural responsiveness. Where government provision falls short, individuals and community organisations play a substantial complementary role — through direct service volunteering, NGO-funded programming, and advocacy that raises awareness of ethnic minority communities’ needs among policymakers and the public. The literature is consistent in suggesting that durable improvement requires coordinated effort across government, community organisations, and families, rather than any single actor working in isolation (Phakakorn et al., 2018, 2019; Ratanasuwan et al., 2020).</p>
<h3 class="sub" id="building-resilience-in-children-facing-adversity">Building Resilience in Children Facing Adversity</h3>
<p>Resilience — the capacity to adapt and thrive despite adversity — is widely regarded as the primary protective mechanism buffering children from the negative sequelae of ACEs (Ortiz, 2019). Five components of resilience-building recur across the literature.</p>
<p><strong>Trusted adult relationships.</strong> The presence of a consistent, caring adult — a parent, teacher, or mentor — is among the most robust predictors of childhood resilience. Ashton et al. (2021) found that access to a trusted adult decreases as ACE count increases, but that even one or two such relationships substantially raise the resilience resources a child can draw on; these relationships provide emotional security and support the development of self-esteem and problem-solving capacity.</p>
<p><strong>Early childhood education.</strong> Quality early childhood education provides a safe, structured environment in which cognitive, social, and emotional skills can develop, and is often the first setting in which developmental delays or behavioural concerns are identified (Thai Ministry of Education, 2020; Walker &amp; Walsh, 2015). For ethnic minority children specifically, enrolment can also function as a structural bridge to later access to public schooling and identification documentation, extending the benefit of early education beyond the classroom (Phakakorn et al., 2018).</p>
<p><strong>Innovative interventions.</strong> Music- and movement-based interventions offer a non-verbal channel through which children can process traumatic experience while building self-regulation, self-esteem, and social connection (McFerran &amp; Rickson, 2014; Nijs &amp; Nicolaou, 2021).</p>
<p><strong>Early detection and intervention.</strong> Felitti and Anda (2010) emphasise that timely identification — through screening tools that assess ACE exposure and existing protective factors — allows support to be tailored to a child’s specific circumstances rather than applied generically, and is more effective the earlier it occurs.</p>
<p><strong>Collaborative, multi-level effort.</strong> No single actor can address resilience in isolation. Effective approaches integrate trauma-informed practice across families, schools, healthcare settings, and community programmes, supported by ongoing practitioner training (Bronfenbrenner, 1979).</p>
<p>Reviewing factors that differentiate resilient from non-resilient outcomes, Masten and Barnes (2018) identify positive appraisal style — the capacity to reframe adversity constructively — and strong executive function as central individual-level resilience factors, alongside parenting practices, maternal mental health, and consistent household routines as key family-level factors. At the same time, ACEs remain a robust risk factor for depression; Elmore et al. (2020) found that resilience mediates this relationship, meaning that interventions which build resilience may simultaneously reduce depression risk even where ACE exposure itself cannot be changed. This mediating role gives resilience-building practical value as an intervention target independent of primary ACE prevention.</p>
<h3 class="sub" id="synthesis-and-research-gap">Synthesis and Research Gap</h3>
<p>This literature establishes that ACEs carry serious, well-documented long-term costs, and that resilience — supported by trusted relationships, quality early education, and coordinated multi-level effort — is the primary mechanism through which those costs can be mitigated. However, the evidence base underpinning this model is drawn predominantly from North American and European populations. Comparatively little is known about how these mechanisms operate among ethnic minority families in Southeast Asia, where structural disadvantage, cultural norms around parenting and education, and the role of preschool enrolment in determining access to public services differ meaningfully from the contexts in which the existing literature was generated. This study addresses that gap by examining parent- and teacher-reported data from ethnic minority communities in Northern Thailand, combining quantitative modelling of survey responses with thematic analysis of interview data to characterise both the prevalence of protective factors and the practical strategies through which they are enacted.</p>

</div>
</section>

<section class="block band-a" id="method">
<div class="block-inner">
<h2 class="sec-title">Method</h2>

<h3 class="sub" id="design">Design</h3>
<p>This study used a concurrent mixed-methods design (Creswell &amp; Creswell, 2018), combining quantitative questionnaire data with qualitative semi-structured interview data to provide a comprehensive picture of ACEs and resilience-related factors in the study communities. Quantitative data allowed testing of associations between demographic/contextual predictors and item-level survey responses; qualitative data allowed the specific strategies underlying those associations to be described in participants’ own terms. Data collection took place in ethnic minority communities in Chiang Mai and Chiang Rai provinces, Northern Thailand, between March 2022 and June 2023.</p>
<h3 class="sub" id="participants">Participants</h3>
<p>The total study sample comprised 224 participants. Questionnaire data were collected from 50 parents/caregivers and 99 teachers/practitioners (<em>N</em> = 149). Semi-structured interviews were conducted with a subset of 15 parents/caregivers and 50 teachers/practitioners. Parent/caregiver participants were drawn predominantly from the Tai ethnic group and varied in age, education, and household income; teacher/practitioner participants varied in role, workplace setting, and years of experience in early childhood education. Participants were recruited through convenience and snowball sampling.</p>
<h3 class="sub" id="procedure">Procedure</h3>
<p>Data were collected through three complementary methods. <strong>Questionnaire surveys</strong> were administered on paper and online to parents/caregivers and teachers/practitioners, collecting demographic information together with Likert-scale items on ACEs, parental care, early childhood education and welfare, and perceived barriers to support. <strong>Semi-structured interviews</strong> were conducted at kindergartens and schools across the study sites during May and June 2023, exploring participants’ direct experiences and perspectives in greater depth than the survey format allowed. <strong>Field observations</strong> in kindergartens, schools, and community settings provided contextual information used to interpret survey and interview findings.</p>
<h3 class="sub" id="instruments">Instruments</h3>
<p>The <strong>parent/caregiver questionnaire</strong> comprised ten sections covering demographic information, perceptions of ACEs (items 13–20), parental care (21–25), early childhood education and welfare (26–33), perceptions of education and parental care (34–40), perceived barriers to supporting children with ACEs (41–45), parents’ own ACE history (46–51), household environment (52–57), perceived benefits of combined parental/educational support (58–62), and access to state-provided services (63–65). The <strong>teacher/practitioner questionnaire</strong> comprised six sections covering demographic information, perceptions of ACEs (items 9–16), early childhood education and welfare (17–24), perceptions of these programmes (25–30), confidence in supporting affected children (31–34), and perceived barriers to providing support (35–39). Full item wording is provided in Appendices A and B. Both instruments were developed from the literature review, refined through cognitive pre-testing (Collins, 2003), and reviewed by subject-matter experts for clarity and cultural appropriateness prior to administration.</p>
<p>Interview protocols (Appendices C and D) used open-ended questions that moved from participants’ direct experience of ACEs, through specific coping and support strategies used at home or in the classroom, to perceived barriers and policy-relevant recommendations.</p>
<h3 class="sub" id="hypotheses">Hypotheses</h3>
<p><strong>H1:</strong> Parental care, early childhood education, and community services are positively associated with resilience-related perceptions among ethnic minority children in Northern Thailand. <strong>H2:</strong> Resilience is positively associated with healthy developmental outcomes among ethnic minority children in Northern Thailand.</p>
<p>The corresponding null hypotheses (no association in either case) were tested against these alternatives.</p>
<h3 class="sub" id="data-analysis">Data Analysis</h3>
<p><strong>Quantitative analysis.</strong> Descriptive statistics characterised the demographic profile of each sample and the distribution of responses to each questionnaire item. Because Shapiro–Wilk tests indicated significant departure from normality for the large majority of items (consistent with ordinal Likert-type response data), generalised linear models (GLMs) were used in preference to standard linear regression to test whether demographic and contextual predictors improved model fit relative to a null (intercept-only) model, for each survey item in turn (Brown &amp; Green, 2017; Garcia et al., 2021). Model comparison used likelihood-ratio chi-square tests on the deviance difference between null (H₀) and full (H₁) models, with Akaike (AIC) and Bayesian (BIC) information criteria reported alongside. Analyses were conducted in JASP (version 0.18.3.0).</p>
<p><strong>Qualitative analysis.</strong> Interview transcripts were analysed using inductive thematic analysis (Braun et al., 2019), following the stages of familiarisation, initial coding, theme identification, iterative refinement through constant comparison, and organisation into a coherent thematic framework. Coding was conducted in Taguette (version 1.4.1).</p>
<p><strong>Note on demographic variables.</strong> Several demographic variables (e.g., parent age, education, income; teacher age, education, position) were recorded as ordinal categories rather than continuous measures. Descriptive statistics for these variables (Table 1) should be read as describing the <em>coded category</em> (e.g., “category 3 of 5”) rather than a value in original units (e.g., years of age); the original source draft repeatedly translated category means directly into implied real-world units (for example, treating a mean age-category score of 3.12 as “31.2 years”), which is not a valid inference without the underlying category boundaries. This report uses category-level language throughout and the category boundaries (e.g., what age range “category 3” represents) should be confirmed against the original instrument before any year/Baht-denominated values are reported externally.</p>

</div>
</section>

