<h3 class="sub">Predictors of Item-Level Responses: Generalised Linear Models</h3>
<p>For each item, a GLM tested whether demographic and contextual predictors (full model, H&#8321;) improved fit relative to a null model (H&#8320;), using a likelihood-ratio &chi;&sup2; test on the deviance difference.</p>

<div class="sig-chart" role="img" aria-label="31 of 48 parent items significant, 65 percent. 11 of 31 teacher items significant, 35 percent.">
  <div class="sig-row">
    <span class="sig-label">Parents / caregivers</span>
    <div class="sig-track"><div class="sig-fill ochre" style="width:65%"><span class="sig-fill-text">31 / 48 items &middot; 65%</span></div></div>
  </div>
  <div class="sig-row">
    <span class="sig-label">Teachers / practitioners</span>
    <div class="sig-track"><div class="sig-fill madder" style="width:35%"><span class="sig-fill-text">11 / 31 items &middot; 35%</span></div></div>
  </div>
  <p class="sig-caption">Share of questionnaire items for which demographic/contextual predictors significantly improved model fit (<em>p</em> &lt; .05)</p>
</div>

<p>Among parents/caregivers, non-significant items clustered around beliefs about ACEs in the abstract, parents&rsquo; own ACE history and disclosure, and household resource access &mdash; areas where unmeasured factors such as stigma or service availability likely carry more explanatory weight than age, education, income, or family size. Among teachers/practitioners, significant items concentrated in early ACE-perception and welfare-barrier items, while confidence and classroom-practice items showed little demographic differentiation &mdash; suggesting these perceptions are shaped more by shared professional training or school culture than by individual background.</p>

