<h3 class="sub">Thematic Analysis of Interview Data</h3>
<p>Thematic analysis of interviews with 15 parents/caregivers and 50 teachers/practitioners identified consistent strategies for promoting resilience, organised below by respondent group.</p>

<p class="strategy-lead">Parents' and caregivers' strategies</p>
<div class="strategy-grid">
  <div class="strategy-card">
    <p class="strategy-name">Active listening</p>
    <p>The foundation of family communication: attentive engagement with children's concerns built trust, surfaced the causes of distress, and gave children confidence that support would be available.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="strategy-card">
    <p class="strategy-name">Promoting autonomy</p>
    <p>Age-appropriate decisions within a safe framework built independence and critical thinking; confidence grew as children experienced the consequences of their own choices.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="strategy-card">
    <p class="strategy-name">Supporting academic &amp; personal interests</p>
    <p>Active engagement with children's curiosity, beyond direct academic help, linked to motivation and emotional development.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="strategy-card">
    <p class="strategy-name">Emotional &amp; physical presence</p>
    <p>Simply being consistently available was foundational to children's sense of security and belonging.</p>
  </div>
</div>

<p class="strategy-lead">Teachers' and practitioners' strategies</p>
<div class="strategy-grid">
  <div class="strategy-card">
    <p class="strategy-name">Safe, supportive classrooms</p>
    <p>Consistent routines and open communication were essential given many children carry the impact of family conflict or substance use at home.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="strategy-card">
    <p class="strategy-name">Teaching emotional regulation</p>
    <p>Direct coping-skills instruction, paired with individualised support and parent collaboration.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="strategy-card">
    <p class="strategy-name">Building positive relationships</p>
    <p>Trusted adults and family members formed a protective system supporting trust, self-esteem, and belonging.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="strategy-card">
    <p class="strategy-name">Strengths-based approach</p>
    <p>Shifting focus from weaknesses to strengths, particularly important for countering negative self-perception after adversity.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="strategy-card">
    <p class="strategy-name">Collaboration with services</p>
    <p>Extending classroom support into a wider network of therapists, community organisations, and families.</p>
  </div>
</div>

<p><strong>The role of early education and welfare access.</strong> Participants across both groups described early education as contributing to resilience through several channels: educational incentives (scholarships, meal programmes), cognitive and creative development, emotional and social growth through structured peer interaction, and financial relief that indirectly supports children's wellbeing by reducing household stress. Reported barriers to access included selective admission criteria, scheduling conflicts with parents' work, limited transport, and &mdash; most consistently &mdash; financial cost.</p>

<p><strong>Convergence between parent and teacher accounts.</strong> Both groups independently identified active listening and emotionally secure environments as central to resilience-building (Centre of Excellence for Early Childhood Development, 2014; Herndon &amp; Waggoner, 2021; Long &amp; Evans, 2021; Morgan et al., 2016), and both emphasised that resilience-building is inherently collaborative rather than the responsibility of any single adult &mdash; parents drawing on extended family (Howard &amp; Johnson, 2000; Đurišić &amp; Bunijevac, 2017; Durlak, 1998), teachers on external services and community organisations (Tanyu et al., 2020). This convergence across independently interviewed groups strengthens confidence that these strategies reflect substantive, shared practice rather than artefacts of either group's framing.</p>

</div>
</section>

<section class="block band-a" id="discussion">
<div class="block-inner">
<h2 class="sec-title">Discussion</h2>

<p>This study examined how parental care, early childhood education, and community support relate to resilience-related perceptions among ethnic minority children in Northern Thailand, drawing on quantitative survey data from parents/caregivers and teachers/practitioners alongside qualitative interview data from both groups. Findings are discussed below in relation to the four research questions guiding this study.</p>
<p><strong>Challenges and manifestations of ACEs.</strong> Both quantitative and qualitative data confirmed that ethnic minority families and educators in this study perceive ACEs as a significant and multifaceted challenge. Notably, demographic and contextual predictors explained variation in parents’ <em>general beliefs</em> about ACEs and early education more consistently than they explained parents’ reports of their <em>own</em> household’s resource access or disclosure of personal ACE history (items 53–56, 59, 63) — areas where over 40% of surveyed parents reported having experienced ACEs themselves. This gap between general belief and personal disclosure is consistent with the broader literature’s emphasis on stigma as a barrier to support-seeking (Bellis et al., 2019), and suggests that intergenerational programming — support that explicitly addresses parents’ own unresolved adversity alongside their children’s — may be necessary to close it (Dong et al., 2004).</p>
<p><strong>Parental care and resilience.</strong> The active listening, autonomy-promotion, and consistent presence strategies identified in parent interviews align closely with the trusted-adult-relationship mechanism established in the broader resilience literature (Ashton et al., 2021): each strategy functions, in different ways, to maintain the parent as an accessible, responsive source of support. The GLM results add a complementary, population-level perspective: the demographic and contextual factors measured here (age, education, income, family size) meaningfully differentiated how parents responded to roughly two-thirds of survey items, indicating that parental background characteristics are far from incidental to how resilience-related beliefs and practices are reported in this sample, and should be considered when designing family-targeted interventions rather than treated as a uniform population.</p>
<p><strong>The role of early childhood education.</strong> Teachers’ and parents’ accounts converged on early education’s role in building cognitive, social, and emotional capacity, and in relieving financial pressure on families through scholarships and meal programmes — channels that operate alongside, rather than instead of, direct pedagogical benefit. However, the comparatively low rate of significant demographic prediction among teacher/practitioner items (35%, versus 65% for parents) suggests that teachers’ confidence, perceived effectiveness, and classroom practice are more uniform across age, role, and experience than parents’ equivalent beliefs are across their own demographic range. One plausible explanation is that teacher practice in this sample is shaped more by shared professional training and school-level culture than by individual background — though this study’s design cannot distinguish that explanation from the alternative possibility that the demographic variables measured here (age, position, workplace, experience) simply capture less of the variation relevant to teacher practice than the equivalent variables capture for parents. Future research incorporating measures of training history, supervisory support, or school-level resourcing would help distinguish between these explanations.</p>
<p><strong>Community support systems.</strong> Both parent and teacher accounts emphasised that resilience-building functions as a collective rather than individual effort — extending, for parents, to grandparents and extended family, and for teachers, to therapists and community organisations. This is consistent with prior accounts of resilience as embedded in nested family, school, and community systems (Bronfenbrenner, 1979), and suggests that interventions seeking to strengthen any single layer of support (e.g., parent training alone, or teacher training alone) may have limited reach unless paired with efforts to strengthen the connective tissue between layers — particularly the financial and structural barriers (cost, transport, admission criteria) that both groups identified as limiting access to early education in the first place.</p>

</div>
</section>
<section class="block band-b" id="limitations">
<div class="block-inner">
<h2 class="sec-title">Limitations</h2>

<p>This study has several limitations that should inform interpretation of its findings and any subsequent research building on it. First, convenience and snowball sampling limit the generalisability of findings to the broader population of ethnic minority families and educators in Northern Thailand, and may have introduced selection bias toward participants more willing or able to engage with researchers. Second, data collection took place during the COVID-19 pandemic, which constrained access to some communities and may have shaped participants’ circumstances and responses in ways not captured by this design. Third, several demographic variables were collected as ordinal categories without an accompanying coding key available to the present analysis; as noted in the Method, real-world units (years, income brackets) should not be inferred from category means without confirming category boundaries against the original instrument. Fourth, this study relies on self-reported data, which is subject to social desirability bias and recall limitations, particularly for sensitive items concerning personal ACE history. Fifth, the cross-sectional design captures a single point in time and cannot speak to longitudinal or intergenerational outcomes.</p>

</div>
</section>
<section class="block band-a" id="conclusion">
<div class="block-inner">
<h2 class="sec-title">Conclusion</h2>

<p>This study examined protective factors associated with resilience among ethnic minority children exposed to ACEs in Northern Thailand, drawing on parent/caregiver and teacher/practitioner perspectives. Quantitative analysis showed that demographic and contextual factors more strongly differentiated parents’ resilience-related beliefs and practices (significant for 65% of items) than teachers’ equivalent perceptions (significant for 35% of items), pointing to a meaningful difference in how individual variation operates across the two groups. Thematic analysis identified active listening, autonomy promotion, and consistent presence as central parental strategies, and safe environments, emotional-regulation instruction, and strengths-based practice as central teacher strategies — with both groups independently converging on the importance of collaborative, multi-level support extending beyond any single relationship.</p>
<p>Together, these findings suggest that interventions seeking to build resilience in this population should be designed with two complementary tracks in mind: family-centred support that accounts for meaningful demographic variation among parents (including, specifically, support that addresses parents’ own unresolved ACE history), and school-based support that strengthens the professional and structural conditions of teaching practice rather than targeting individual teacher characteristics. Reducing the financial and structural barriers to early education access identified by both groups — cost, transport, and admission criteria — emerges as a shared precondition for either track to reach the children who need it most.</p>

</div>
</section>

