</section>

<section class="block band-a" id="appendices">
<div class="block-inner">
<h2 class="sec-title">Appendices</h2>
<p>Full questionnaire item wording and interview protocols. Item numbers here correspond to those used in Tables 2, 4, 5, and 6 above.</p>
<details class="data-disclosure"><summary>Appendix A: Parent/Caregiver Questionnaire Items</summary><div class="appendix-body">
<p><em>Demographic information:</em> age, gender, education level, occupation, marital status, income level, household size, relationship to child, child’s age, child’s gender, child’s education level, child’s current early childhood education/welfare status.</p>
<p><strong>Section 2 — Perceptions of ACEs (13–20):</strong> Beliefs about whether children with ACEs have difficulty trusting others (13); feel guilty or responsible (14); struggle with emotional regulation (15); have difficulty forming peer relationships (16); struggle academically (17); feel anxious or depressed (18); show elevated risk-taking (19); have difficulty with impulse control (20).</p>
<p><strong>Section 3 — Parental care (21–25):</strong> The role of parents/caregivers in promoting resilience (21); providing a safe, supportive home (22); modelling positive coping (23); listening and providing emotional support (24); involvement in education and welfare (25).</p>
<p><strong>Section 4 — Early childhood education and welfare (26–33):</strong> Perceived contribution of ECE/welfare programmes to resilience (26), safety (27), social-emotional skills (28), academic success (29), peer/adult relationships (30), belonging (31), confidence (32), and overcoming ACE effects (33).</p>
<p><strong>Section 5 — Perceptions of ECE and parental care (34–40):</strong> Beliefs about programme effectiveness (34), importance for resilience (35), prioritisation by government/community (36), universal accessibility (37), the role of parents (38), and personal confidence/preparedness to support one’s own child (39–40).</p>
<p><strong>Section 6 — Perceived barriers (41–45):</strong> Limited resources (41), cultural/language barriers (42), stigma and shame (43), limited trauma-informed training (44), workload/personal constraints (45).</p>
<p><strong>Section 7 — Parents’ own ACE history (46–51):</strong> Personal ACE history (46); effect on parenting style (47); help-seeking (48); disclosure to child (49); perceived effect on child’s resilience (50) and reasoning (51).</p>
<p><strong>Section 8 — Household environment (52–57):</strong> Safety (52), family/community support (53), access to resources (54), healthcare access (55), nutrition/clean water (56), access to higher education (57).</p>
<p><strong>Section 9 — Perceived benefits of combined support (58–62):</strong> Parental care, ECE, and welfare working together (58); parents’ role in academic success (59); ECE/welfare supporting parents (60); benefits of parental involvement (61); benefits of strong teacher–parent relationships (62).</p>
<p><strong>Section 10 — Access to state-provided services (63–65):</strong> Convenience of accessing services for one’s child (63) or oneself (64); open-ended factors influencing the decision to seek support (65).</p>
</div></details><details class="data-disclosure"><summary>Appendix B: Teacher/Practitioner Questionnaire Items</summary><div class="appendix-body">
<p><em>Demographic information:</em> age, gender, nationality background, educational background, position, workplace, years working in early childhood education, ACE-related professional development, open-ended work experience with ethnic minority children.</p>
<p><strong>Section 2 — Perceptions of ACEs (9–16):</strong> Parallel to parent items 13–20 (trust, guilt, emotional regulation, peer relationships, academic struggle, anxiety/depression, risk-taking, impulse control).</p>
<p><strong>Section 3 — Early childhood education and welfare (17–24):</strong> Parallel to parent items 26–33.</p>
<p><strong>Section 4 — Perceptions of ECE/welfare (25–30):</strong> Programme effectiveness (25); importance of promoting resilience (26); need for government/community support (27); educator training and resourcing needs (28); programme’s role in resilience (29); universal accessibility (30).</p>
<p><strong>Section 5 — Confidence in supporting affected children (31–34):</strong> Confidence providing support (31); comfort discussing children’s experiences (32); feeling equipped to foster resilience (33); feeling supported by colleagues/community (34).</p>
<p><strong>Section 6 — Perceived barriers (35–39):</strong> Limited resources (35), cultural/language barriers (36), stigma (37), limited trauma-informed training (38), caseload/workload (39).</p>
</div></details><details class="data-disclosure"><summary>Appendix C: Parent/Caregiver Interview Protocol</summary><div class="appendix-body">
<ol type="1">
<li>Have you or your children had any adverse childhood experiences you would like to share?</li>
<li>In your opinion, do adverse childhood experiences impact a child’s development and wellbeing?</li>
<li>What role does parental supervision play in promoting emotional resilience for children who have experienced unwanted childhood events?</li>
<li>Can you provide examples of how you have helped your children cope with adverse childhood experiences?</li>
<li>How do you specifically support your child’s resilience at home?</li>
<li>To what extent can early childhood education and welfare programmes contribute to promoting emotional resilience in children who have experienced unwanted childhood events?</li>
<li>What options for early education and welfare programmes are available for these children?</li>
<li>What challenges or obstacles arise when accessing services or attending early childhood education and welfare programmes?</li>
<li>What additional measures could be implemented at the policy or community level to support children who have experienced traumatic events, while promoting emotional resilience through preschool education, welfare services, and parental supervision?</li>
</ol>
</div></details><details class="data-disclosure"><summary>Appendix D: Teacher/Practitioner Interview Protocol</summary><div class="appendix-body">
<ol type="1">
<li>Could you describe your previous experience working with children who have had adverse childhood experiences?</li>
<li>In your opinion, how do adverse childhood experiences impact a child’s development and overall wellbeing?</li>
<li>What role can early childhood education programmes play in promoting emotional resilience for children who have experienced adversity?</li>
<li>Can you share examples of cases where early childhood education has helped improve the lives of children who have experienced trauma under your care?</li>
<li>How do you support students who have experienced adversity in your classroom or childcare facility?</li>
<li>What strategies do you use when engaging with parents or caregivers to help their child overcome traumatic events?</li>
<li>What challenges or obstacles arise when supporting children with adverse experiences?</li>
<li>Should early childhood education policies be culturally sensitive and inclusive of minority groups to ensure equal learning opportunities?</li>
<li>Are there specific training programmes or resources that are helpful when working with students who have faced adversity?</li>
<li>What additional steps can be taken at a policy or community level to promote emotional resilience through education and welfare services for young children affected by trauma?</li>
</ol>
<p><em>Note.</em> Tables 5 and 6 in the Results section present the complete generalised linear model output for all parent/caregiver and teacher/practitioner questionnaire items respectively; these consolidate and supersede the separate regression appendices in the original draft, which substantially duplicated this material across the main text and two further appendices.</p>
</div></details>
</div>
</section><footer>
  <p>Adverse Childhood Experiences and Resilience Development in Ethnic Minority Preschool Children: The Role of Parental Care, Early Childhood Education, and Community Support in Northern Thailand. Research report, March 2024.</p>
  <p>Prapassara Thanosawan, PhD &middot; Nuttapa Thanosawan, PhD &middot; Correspondence on request.</p>
